PRIORITY 1 TABLES & INDEXES
 * no heap tuple larger than page may begenerated
 * only support for heap_table, blob_store(for all extended columns), and btree_index(key size lesser than 1/3 of DB page)
  * btree_index will have an entry that store key, tuple_location(root_page_id, page_id, tuple_index)
  * root_page_id allows us to know about all versions of the table effectively picking the right altered version from the right table
  * alter table creates new versions not modify old tables
 * insert tuple is a set of mini transactions
   * insert to heap_table with right mvcc header but no column data
   * hold latch on the heap_page and commit the previous mini tx
   * set inline and extended attributes one by one
   * for inline attributes do nothing
   * for extended types commit current mini tx and start a new one
   * open blob type tuple large types bases appended
   * append bytes in chunk of 1 MB and commit after every time updating the heap page tuple in that mini transaction, to preserve head (NOP if the head remains unchanged)
   * once all columns are set commit the final minitransaction
   * then finally create individual index entries and insert into all the indices
   * if any mini transaction aborts vaccum will take care of clearing it based on it's mvcc header
 * to update do what you did with insert but before that create a mini transaction to write xmax to the older tuple version
 * to delete just write your xmax to older tuple version
 * on vaccum
   * first delete all the index entries one by one in individual mini transactions
   * then destroy all extended types by discarding 1 MB at a time, and intermittently setting the new heads
   * finally delete the heap page tuple in context
 * in all these operations take enough number of buffers for these operators that use these functions
 * modifications check locks and mvcc visibility both
 * only tuple locks (root_page_id, page_id, tuple_index) will be available first (root_page_id belongs to the heap_table in context)






